dataStructure.title: Social Status
dataStructure.description: This CRF Module contains data elements that are collected to further describe the study population beyond the typical demographic variables. Examples of items included are education level and marital/partner status.

dataStructure.title: Protocol Deviations
dataStructure.description: This CRF Module records any protocol deviations that may occur during the study for a given participant/subject.

dataStructure.title: Screening Log
dataStructure.description: The Screening Log is an essential document that records all individuals who entered pre-screening or screening. It details the reasons why an individual was not enrolled or provides the enrollment date if he/she was enrolled into the study. It is also an effort to capture the screening barriers and issues related to enrolling participants/subjects into the clinical study protocol.

dataStructure.title: Adverse Events
dataStructure.description: The Adverse Events (AEs) CRF Module documents medical events that occur to a participant/subject once enrolled in a study. The AE form includes: the AE start date, severity, relatedness, outcome, and an indication of whether the event is serious.

dataStructure.title: Behavioral History
dataStructure.description: This CRF Module is for studies that need to collect information related to tobacco and alcohol use.

dataStructure.title: Family History
dataStructure.description: The Family History at Baseline CRF Module captures data about whether a specific list of diseases/conditions run in the participant's/subject's family (i.e., blood relatives only).

dataStructure.title: Inclusion and Exclusion Criteria
dataStructure.description: The Inclusion and Exclusion Criteria CRF Module specifies the characteristics of potential study participants/subjects that must be met prior to enrollment. All Inclusion Criteria must be answered YES and all Exclusion Criteria must be answered NO or N/A in order for the subject to be considered eligible for study participation.

dataStructure.title: Medical History
dataStructure.description: Medical History data are collected to verify the inclusion and exclusion criteria (e.g., no history of cognitive disabilities) and to describe the study population. The Medical History CRF Module captures conditions that EVER occurred at some point in time within a protocol-defined period (e.g., the last 12 months).

dataStructure.title: Demographics
dataStructure.description: This CRF Module contains data elements that are collected to describe the demographics of the study population. The items are used to compare baseline characteristics among study groups and to identify confounding variables.

dataStructure.title: Study Discontinuation/Completion
dataStructure.description: The Study Discontinuation/Completion CRF Module captures each participant's/subject's status at the end of the study. It provides an anchor for quality control and analysis. The status, in aggregate, also defines the study population -- those completed, lost, etc.

dataStructure.title: Questionnaire for Impulsive-Compulsive Behaviors in Parkinson's Disease (QUIP) (Long form)
Questionnaire for Impulsive-Compulsive Behaviors in Parkinson's Disease (QUIP) (Short form)
Prior and Concomitant Medications
dataStructure.description: Collecting medications taken prior to the study in a defined time window (e.g. 30 days) is important when there may be potential interactions with the study intervention. The Prior and Concomitant Medications CRF Module should be filled out at all visits throughout the study period.

dataStructure.title: Death Report
dataStructure.description: The Death Report CRF Module should only be completed in the event of the participant's/subject's death while enrolled in the study. It captures the date, time and the medical reason death is attributed.

dataStructure.title: Study Drug Compliance
dataStructure.description: The Study Drug Compliance form tracks the expected (i.e., prescribed) vs. actual use of the study drug by an individual participant/subject.

dataStructure.title: Structured Clinical Interview for Pathological Gambling (SCI-PG)
Study Drug Dosing
dataStructure.description: This CRF Module tracks the study intervention dosing regimen for an individual participant/subject across the duration of the study in a log format. For each dosing record the Start Date, Stop Date, Dose Amount, Dose Unit, and Dose Frequency are recorded.

dataStructure.title: Laboratory Tests and Tracking
dataStructure.description: Contains elements that can be used to collect laboratory test results that are routinely administered in clinical trials of pharmacological interventions to assess participant/subject safety, and to record when samples were collected for each participant/subject.

dataStructure.title: Vital Signs
dataStructure.description: This CRF Module captures vital signs, weight, and height. Vital signs can help assess the safety of the intervention and monitor the health of the participants/subjects throughout the study period. Height and weight are commonly collected at the baseline visit.

dataStructure.title: Disability Rating Scale (DRS)
dataStructure.description: The DRS contains 8 items. The first three items ("Eye Opening," "Communication Ability", and "Motor Response") are a modification of the Glasgow Coma Scale (scored in reverse), and reflect impairment and level of consciousness. Cognitive ability for "Feeding", "Toileting" and "Grooming" reflect level of disability. "Level of Functioning" and "Employability" reflect handicap.

dataStructure.title: Health and Behavior Inventory (HBI) Child Version
dataStructure.description: The HBI consists of 20 items that measure the frequency of post-concussive symptoms. There are three versions of the inventory - Child, Parent Current Version and Parent Retrospective Version. The Parent Retrospective Version is used for rating pre-injury symptoms retrospectively.

dataStructure.title: Physical Exam
dataStructure.description: The physical exam is generally administered at screening and/or baseline to determine study eligibility. It may also be administered at follow-up visits to track a participant's/subject's physical status. This CRF Module captures the physical exam results.

dataStructure.title: Informed Consent and Enrollment
dataStructure.description: It is important to collect the date of certain study milestones, such as informed consent, study enrollment and randomization, from both an administrative and human subjects' protection standpoint. This CRF Module captures those key pieces of data.

dataStructure.title: Electrocardiogram (ECG)
dataStructure.description: The Electrocardiogram (ECG) CRF Module is used to document the time, date, and results of this cardiac function test.

dataStructure.title: Craig Handicap and Assessment Reporting Technique (CHART-SF) - Interview version
dataStructure.description: The CHART-SF contains 19 items. There are six subscales consisting of: Physical Independence, Cognitive Independence, Mobility, Occupation, Social Integration, and Economic Self-Sufficiency.

dataStructure.title: Health and Behavior Inventory (HBI) Parent Current Version
dataStructure.description: The HBI consists of 20 items that measure the frequency of post-concussive symptoms. There are three versions of the inventory - Child, Parent Current Version and Parent Retrospective Version. The Parent Retrospective Version is used for rating pre-injury symptoms retrospectively.

dataStructure.title: Health and Behavior Inventory (HBI) Parent Retrospective Version
dataStructure.description: The HBI consists of 20 items that measure the frequency of post-concussive symptoms. There are three versions of the inventory - Child, Parent Current Version and Parent Retrospective Version. The Parent Retrospective Version is used for rating pre-injury symptoms retrospectively.

dataStructure.title: Study Therapies Compliance
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that tracks participation in any therapies by the individual study participants/ subjects. (Examples of CDEs included: Date of therapy; Sources of therapy; Expected length of session in minutes; and Actual length of session in minut

dataStructure.title: Demographics
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that are collected to describe the demographics of the study population relevant to TBI research.

dataStructure.title: Socioeconomic Status
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that are collected to describe the social status of the study population relevant to TBI research.

dataStructure.title: Significant Medical History
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that are collected to describe the medical history of the study population relevant to TBI research.

dataStructure.title: Behavioral History
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements related to the behavioral history of the subject/participant regarding use/ consumption of tobacco, alcoholic beverages, and illicit drugs. (Examples of CDEs included: Past use and Use in last three months of Tobacco products, Alcoholic beverages, Sedatives/Sleeping pills, Cannabis, and Other drugs.)

dataStructure.title: Ohio State University TBI Identification Method Short Form
dataStructure.description: Ohio State University TBI Identification Method-Short Form (OSU TBI-ID-SF) is a shortened version of a structured interview developed using recommendations from the CDC for the detection of history of exposure to traumatic brain injury. It elicits self- or proxy-reports of TBI occurring over a person's lifetime according to selected summary indices.

dataStructure.title: Screening for TBI in Military Personnel
dataStructure.description: This screening instruments contains four questions/data elements that are collected to help in screening military personnel for possible traumatic brain injury.

dataStructure.title: Injury Presentation - Early/Late
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that are collected to describe the participant's/subject's presentation to medical care for the injury, which may be immediately after the injury (early) or after a period of time (late).

dataStructure.title: Type, Place, Cause and Mechanism of Injury
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that are collected to describe the circumstances of the injury, such as how and where it occurred, and the type of injury.

dataStructure.title: Injuries and Injury Severity
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that are collected to further describe the injury and classify its severity.

dataStructure.title: Baseline Risk Assessment
dataStructure.description: This module is a risk assessment for mortality or unfavorable outcome following traumatic brain injury expressed as fraction or percentage. It contains data elements that can be derived or pulled from other CRF modules and codified in a format to be entered into the prognostic model. The IMPACT prognostic model is used for moderate and severe TBI and the model proposed by CRASH trial is used for mild TBI.

dataStructure.title: Second Insults and Other Complications
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that are collected to describe insults and complications the participant/subject experienced secondary to the injury.

dataStructure.title: Discharge Status
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements related to discharge status of the subject/participant from hospital or ICU following traumatic brain injury treatment. (Examples of CDEs included: Discharge status, Discharge date, and Discharge destination.)

dataStructure.title: ER Destination
dataStructure.description: Contains information related to location subject/participant is discharged to following emergency room (ER) treatment for traumatic brain injury.

dataStructure.title: Neurological Assessment: Glasgow Coma Scale (GCS) and Pupils
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that are collected to assess severity of the injury using the Glasgow Coma Scale and an examination of the participant's/subject's pupils.

dataStructure.title: Neurological Assessment: LOC, PTA, and AOC
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements related to neurological assessment of the study participant/subject regarding loss of consciousness (LOC), post traumatic amnesia (PTA) and alternation of consciousness (AOC).

dataStructure.title: Neurological Assessment: TBI Symptoms and Signs
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that are collected to characterize the symptoms the participant/subject experiences and other signs related to the injury.

dataStructure.title: Vital Signs and Blood Gases
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements related to vital signs and other physiological measurements commonly used in TBI clinical research studies.

dataStructure.title: Laboratory Tests
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements related to laboratory tests commonly used in TBI clinical research studies.

dataStructure.title: Imaging
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements related to imaging studies (e.g., MRI and CT studies) commonly used in TBI clinical research studies.

dataStructure.title: ER/Admission Therapeutic Procedures
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that capture therapeutic procedures the participant/subject received upon admission to the hospital and/or treatment in the emergency room.

dataStructure.title: Post Discharge/Outpatient Treatment
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that capture the participant's/subject's course of treatment post-discharge.

dataStructure.title: Informed Consent
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that documents the participant's/subject's consent to participate in the clinical research protocol.

dataStructure.title: Glasgow Outcome Scale (GOS)
dataStructure.description: The GOS is a one item scale with 5 possible ratings - Dead, Vegetative State, Severe Disability, Moderate Disability, and Good Recovery.

dataStructure.title: Glasgow Outcome Scale Extended (GOSE)
dataStructure.description: The GOSE is a revision of the GOS that divides the upper three ratings into upper and lower categories - lower severe disability, upper severe disability, lower moderate disability, upper moderate disability, lower good recovery, upper good recovery.

dataStructure.title: Glasgow Outcome Scale Extended (GOSE) Pediatric Revision
dataStructure.description: The GOSE Peds uses the same 8-point scale as the GOSE, but a structured interview appropriate for children is used to arrive at the result on the scale.

dataStructure.title: Family Assessment Device (FAD)
dataStructure.description: The FAD is a 60 item self-report instrument with responses rated on a 4-point Likert scale from strongly agree to strongly disagree. There is a General Functioning scale and six subscales -- Problem Solving, Communication, Roles, Affective Responsiveness, Affective Involvement, and Behavior Control.

dataStructure.title: Military Acute Concussion Evaluation (MACE)
dataStructure.description: The Military Acute Concussion Evaluation (MACE) is the most widely used screening evaluation for acute concussion in military personnel. The MACE is conducted up to 72 hours following an injury and only if alteration of consciousness or loss of consciousness is present. The evaluation consists of a history section, neurological evaluation, and a scored cognitive screen of orientation, immediate and delayed recall, and concentration. Alternate forms can be used to monitor recovery and aid in decisions about returning to duty. It is currently undergoing additional validation.

dataStructure.title: Satisfaction with Life Scale
dataStructure.description: The SWLS consists of 5 items answered on a 7-point Likert scale ranging from 1=strongly disagree to 7=strongly agree.

dataStructure.title: Neurobehavioral Symptom Inventory
dataStructure.description: The severity of each symptom on the NSI is measured using a 5-item scale (0-none to 4-very severe) that asks patients to indicate the extent to which each symptom has disturbed them in the previous 2 weeks. The NSI total score is the sum of severity ratings of the 22 symptoms. Cluster scores (domains: physical, cognitive, affective, and sensory) were derived.

dataStructure.title: Alcohol, Smoking, and Substance Use Involvement Screening Test (ASSIST)
dataStructure.description: The ASSIST uses eight questions to query about the use of tobacco, alcohol, cannabis, cocaine, amphetamine-type stimulants, inhalants, sedatives, hallucinogens, opioids and other drugs. For most participants, the measure can be completed within 10 minutes.

dataStructure.title: Alcohol Use Disorders Identification Test: Self-Report Version (AUDIT)
dataStructure.description: The AUDIT consists of 10 items which are used to assess excessive drinking, signs of dependence and harmful use in the past year.

dataStructure.title: Center for Epidemiologic Studies-Depression Scale (CES-D)
dataStructure.description: The Center for Epidemiologic Studies Depression Scale (CES-D) is a widely used screening scale for depression. It consists of six subscales of depressed mood, feelings of guilt and worthlessness, feelings of helplessness and hopelessness, psychomotor retardation, loss of appetite, and sleep disturbance. The CES-D queries a patient's depression symptoms in the last week, with each question is scored on a 4-point Likert scale ranging from 0 (rarely/none of the time) to 3 (most/all of the time). Scores for items 4, 8, 12, and 16 are reversed before summing all items to yield a total score. A score of 16 or higher has been used to indicate highly depressive symptoms.

dataStructure.title: Family Assessment Device (FAD)
dataStructure.description: The FAD is a 60 item self-report instrument with responses rated on a 4-point Likert scale from strongly agree to strongly disagree. There is a General Functioning scale and six subscales -- Problem Solving, Communication, Roles, Affective Responsiveness, Affective Involvement, and Behavior Control.

dataStructure.title: Patient Health Questionnaire - 9 (PHQ-9)
dataStructure.description: PHQ-9 provides a reliable and valid measure of depression severity and also yields a DSM-IV criteria based diagnosis of a depressive disorder. This 9 item measure asks subjects whether and how often they have been bothered by depression related symptoms over the last two weeks, ranging from not at all (0) to nearly every day (3). Based on total score, depression severity ranges from minimal symptoms (5-9) to greater than 20 indicating severe major depression.

dataStructure.title: PTSD Checklist - Civilian (PCL-C)
dataStructure.description: The PCL is a 17-item self-report measure of the DSM-IV symptoms of PTSD. Respondents rate how much they were "bothered by a symptom" on a 5-point scale ranging from 1 ("not at all") to 5 ("extremely").

dataStructure.title: PTSD Checklist - Military (PCL-M)
dataStructure.description: The PCL is a 17-item self-report measure of the DSM-IV symptoms of PTSD. Respondents rate how much they were "bothered by a symptom" on a 5-point scale ranging from 1 ("not at all") to 5 ("extremely").

dataStructure.title: PTSD Checklist - Stressor Specific (PCL-S)
dataStructure.description: The PCL is a 17-item self-report measure of the DSM-IV symptoms of PTSD. Respondents rate how much they were "bothered by a symptom" on a 5-point scale ranging from 1 ("not at all") to 5 ("extremely").

dataStructure.title: Substance Abuse Questions from the TBI Model Systems Database
dataStructure.description: One item queries use of non-prescription or illicit drugs within past year. Two optional items ask for the specific drugs used, and the frequency of use of each drug. Four items assess quantity and frequency of alcohol use in past month, and extent of binge drinking.

dataStructure.title: Galveston Orientation and Amnesia Test (GOAT)
dataStructure.description: The GOAT can be administered to assess the duration of post-traumatic amnesia, including ten items on recovery of orientation to person, place, and time. The duration of retrograde and anterograde amnesia can be assessed. It is appropriate for ages 16 and older.

dataStructure.title: JFK Coma Recovery Scale- Revised
dataStructure.description: The CRS-R consists of twenty-three items comprising six hierarchically-arranged subscales addressing auditory, visual, motor, oromotor/verbal, communication and arousal functions. The lowest item on each subscale represents reflexive activity while the highest items represent cognitively-mediated behaviors.

dataStructure.title: Participation Assessment with Recombined Tools-Objective (PART-O)
dataStructure.description: The PART-O consists of 19 items asking for the frequency that the person engages in various activities within the community. Scores have been standardized based on a population sample. Several scoring options have been examined, providing a total score and 3 subscale scores. A briefer 12-item version is currently being evaluated.

dataStructure.title: Post Discharge Status
dataStructure.description: Describes the status of the participant/subject at selected time points following discharge from the hospital.

dataStructure.title: Death
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements collected in the event of the participant's/subject's death while enrolled in the study. It captures the date, time and medical reason death is attributed.

dataStructure.title: Demographics
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that are collected to describe the demographics of the study population relevant to Parkinson's disease research. (Examples of CDEs included: General CDE demographic elements (gender, race, ethnicity, etc.); handedness; Date of Birth)

dataStructure.title: Family History
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that determine if Parkinson's disease or other related neurological diseases/disorders run in the participant's/ subject's immediate family. (Examples of CDEs included: Number of Family Members; Number with PD or Parkinsonism; Number with Other Neurological Disorder; etc.)

dataStructure.title: Functional Neurosurgery
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements about pre-, intra-, and post-operative guidelines for DBS reports. (Examples of CDEs included: Head Position; Intraoperative Target Verification; L-dopa challenge responses; etc.)

dataStructure.title: History of Early Exposure
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements about the history of being breast fed, sibship/birth order, and preschool attendance. (Examples of CDEs included: Did you attend preschool; Numbers of brothers and sisters; Did your mother breastfeed you; etc.)

dataStructure.title: Infection History
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements about the participant/subject's history of influenza, pneumonia, and meningitis. (Examples of CDEs included: Age at time of pneumonia; First influenza vaccination; Age at time of meningitis; etc.)

dataStructure.title: Medical History of Parkinson's Disease
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements related to the study participant's/ subject's health history when Parkinson's disease was first diagnosed. Particular attention is paid to motor symptoms. (Examples of CDEs included: Diagnostic features/criteria; Initial Motor Symptoms; etc.)

dataStructure.title: MR
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements used to assess function and anatomy in the brain. (Examples of CDEs included: Pulse Sequence; Field Strength; Head Coil; etc.)

dataStructure.title: MRI and Spectroscopy
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements used in imaging studies to visualize internal structures. (Examples of CDEs included: Pre-scan actions; Site of Visual Analysis; etc.)

dataStructure.title: Neuropathology
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements about post mortem brain tissue and disease progression. (Examples of CDEs included: Macroscopic aspects; Alzheimer's type pathology; Lewy body pathology; etc.)

dataStructure.title: Non-Parkinson's Disease Medication Log
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements about the participant/subject's non-PD medication history during study enrollment. (Examples of CDEs included: Macroscopic aspects; Alzheimer's type pathology; Lewy body pathology; etc.)

dataStructure.title: Non-prescribed Drug Use Questionnaire
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements about use of drugs not prescribed by a doctor in the participant/subject's lifetime. (Examples of CDEs included: Year of First Use; Last Year Used; Total Years Used; Frequency of Use; etc.)

dataStructure.title: Parkinson's Disease Medication Log
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements about non-study PD medications the participant/subject has taken during study enrollment. (Examples of CDEs included: Medication Class; Medication Name; Estimated Total Duration Exposure; etc.)

dataStructure.title: PET-SPECT
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements used to measure cellular/tissue change in a participant/subject. (Examples of CDEs included: Radioligand; Quantitative Imaging Outcome; etc.)

dataStructure.title: PD DOC Mini Environmental Risk Questionnaire for Parkinson's Disease Patients Baseline (PD DOC MERQ-PD-B)
dataStructure.description: The mini-environmental risk factor questionnaire (MERQ) is from the Parkinson's Disease Data and Organizing Center (PD-DOC). It contains questions regarding use of medications linked to PD occurrence or progression such as NSAIDs, statins, and hormone replacement therapy.

dataStructure.title: Risk Factor Questionnaire (RFQ) - Physical Activity and Sleep
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements about types of physical activity and amount of sleep the participant/subject received during different phases of life. (Examples of CDEs included: Physical activity and sleep hours from 12-17 years, 18-25 years, 26-35 years, 36-45 years, 46-55 years, 56-65 years, and 66 years and above; etc.)

dataStructure.title: Ohio State University TBI Identification Method Short Form
dataStructure.description: Ohio State University TBI Identification Method-Short Form (OSU TBI-ID-SF) is a shortened version of a structured interview developed using recommendations from the CDC for the detection of history of exposure to traumatic brain injury. It elicits self- or proxy-reports of TBI occurring over a person's lifetime according to selected summary indices.

dataStructure.title: Scales for Outcomes in Parkinson's Disease-Cognitive (SCOPA-COG)
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements to assess specific aspects of cognitive function in Parkinson's disease. (Examples of CDEs included: Memory and Function; Attention; Executive Functions; etc.)

dataStructure.title: Short Portable Mental Status Questionnaire (SPMSQ)
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements about the participant/subject's global cognitive function. (Examples of CDEs included: Current address; Current President; Age; Mother's maiden name; etc.)

dataStructure.title: Addenbrooke's Cognitive Examination Revised (ACE-R)
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements to measure global cognitive function. (Examples of CDEs included assess: Attention and Orientation; Memory; Verbal Fluency; Language and visuospatial skills)

dataStructure.title: Movement Disorder Society - Unified Parkinson's Disease Rating Scale (MDS-UPDRS)
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements about non-motor and motor features of Parkinson's disease. This is the new version of the UPDRS sponsored by the MDS. (Examples of CDEs included: Non-motor examination; Motor examination; etc.)

dataStructure.title: Unified Parkinson's Disease Rating Scale (UPDRS)
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements about non-motor and motor features of Parkinson's disease. (Examples of CDEs included: Non-motor examination; Motor examination; etc.)

dataStructure.title: Other Non-motor Guidelines for CDE Use
dataStructure.description: Contains a summary of the subgroup process in determining the instruments and elements they recommended for Other Non-motor studies in Parkinson's disease.

dataStructure.title: Berlin Questionnaire
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that assess that participant/subject's risk for having sleep apnea. (Examples of CDEs included: Do you snore; How often do you feel tired or fatigued; etc.)

dataStructure.title: Cambridge-Hopkins Restless Legs Syndrome Diagnostic Questionnaire (CH-RLSQ)
dataStructure.description: The Cambridge-Hopkins diagnostic questionnaire for restless leg syndrome (CH-RLSq) was developed with several iterations to include items covering the basic diagnostic features of RLS and to provide some basic differential diagnosis.

dataStructure.title: Drooling Severity and Frequency Scale (DSFS)
dataStructure.description: The Drooling Severity and Frequency Scale (DSFS) is a semi-quantitative assessment of the amount of drooling.

dataStructure.title: Fatigue Severity Scale (FSS) of Sleep Disorders
dataStructure.description: The Fatigue Severity Scale (FSS) of Sleep Disorders is a nine-item questionnaire that assesses the effect of fatigue on daily living.

dataStructure.title: Food Frequency Questionnaire (FFQ)
dataStructure.description: The Food Frequency Questionnaire (FFQ) consists of a list of foods with little descriptive detail, and the respondent answers questions about the frequency of each food on the list.

dataStructure.title: Insomnia Severity Index (ISI)
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that assess the participant/subject's insomnia severity. (Examples of CDEs included: Falling asleep; Staying asleep; Sleep pattern; etc.)

dataStructure.title: Mini Nutritional Assessment (MNA)
dataStructure.description: The MNA is a validated nutrition screening and assessment tool that can identify geriatric patients age 65 and above who are malnourished or at risk of malnutrition.

dataStructure.title: Non-Motor Symptom assessment scale for Parkinson's Disease (NMSS)
dataStructure.description: The Non-Motor Symptoms Scale (NMSS) is an instrument specifically designed for the comprehensive assessment of nonmotor symptoms (NMS) in patients with Parkinson's disease.

dataStructure.title: Rome III Constipation Module
dataStructure.description: This questionnaire was developed to assist physicians, health care professionals and researchers in identifying individuals who have one or more functional gastrointestinal disorders (FGIDs).

dataStructure.title: Scale for Outcomes in Parkinson's Disease Autonomic (SCOPA-AUT)
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that assess the extent in the past month the participant/subject has had problems with bodily functions. (Examples of CDEs included: Difficulty swallowing; Difficulty passing urine; Excessive sweating; etc.)

dataStructure.title: Sialorrhea Clinical Scale for Parkinson's Disease (SCS-PD)
dataStructure.description: The Sialorrhea Clinical Scale for PD (SCS-PD) assesses drooling severity and frequency as well as social and functional impairment from drooling.

dataStructure.title: Sleep Apnea Scale of Sleep Disorders Questionnaire (SA-SDQ)
dataStructure.description: The Sleep Apnea scale of the Sleep Disorders Questionnaire (SA-SDQ) is 12-item validated measure useful as a screening instrument for sleep-related breathing disorders.

dataStructure.title: Stanford Sleepiness Scale (SSS)
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that assess how alert the participant/subject is feeling. (Examples of CDEs included: Feeling active, alert; Functioning at high levels; etc.)

dataStructure.title: STOP Questionnaire
dataStructure.description: The STOP questionnaire is a concise and easy to- use screening tool for obstructive sleep apnea (OSA). It has been developed and validated in surgical patients at preoperative clinics. Combined with body mass index, age, neck size, and gender, it had a high sensitivity, especially for patients with moderate to severe OSA.

dataStructure.title: Survey Screen for Sleep Apnea (SSSA)
dataStructure.description: The symptoms included in the questionnaire are associated with sleep disorders such as sleep apnea-related symptoms, difficulty sleeping symptoms, EDS symptoms, and narcolepsy-like symptoms.

dataStructure.title: Brief Psychiatric Rating Scale (BPRS)
dataStructure.description: The Brief Psychiatric Rating Scale (BPRS) has been widely used in PD psychiatric clinical trials and is the easiest/shortest to administer. It was initially developed for schizophrenia. The instrument should be used in cognitively intact subjects and does not require an informant.

dataStructure.title: Gambling Symptom Assessment Scale (G-SAS)
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements used to evaluate gambling symptoms. (Examples of CDEs included: Urges to Gamble; Thoughts on Gambling; Emotional distress over gambling; etc.)

dataStructure.title: Hamilton Anxiety Rating Scale (HAM-A)
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements which rate the severity of the participant/subject's level of anxiety. (Examples of CDEs included: Anxious mood; Tension; Fears; etc.)

dataStructure.title: Questionnaire about Buying Behavior (QABB)
dataStructure.description: The Buying Questionnaire is a 19-item self-rated questionnaire that measures severity of buying behaviors.

dataStructure.title: Scale for the Assessment of Positive Symptoms (SAPS)
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements which are used to assess positive symptoms such as hallucinations, delusions, bizarre behavior, and positive formal thought disorder that occur primarily in schizophrenia. (Examples of CDEs included: Hallucinations; Delusions; Bizarre Behavior; etc.) .

dataStructure.title: Sexual Compulsivity Scale (SCS)
dataStructure.description: The Sexual Compulsivity Scale is a 10-item self-rated questionnaire that assesses tendencies toward sexual preoccupation.

dataStructure.title: South Oaks Gambling Screen (SOGS)
dataStructure.description: The South Oaks Gambling Screen (SOGS) is a self-rated screening questionnaire and is the most commonly used instrument to screen for pathological or problem gambling in the general population.

dataStructure.title: Parkinson's Impact Scale (PIMS)
dataStructure.description: The 10 item scale measures the impact of Parkinson's disease. This disease specific measure can be completed by the subject or by an interviewer. It is intended for a patient but has been validated in caregivers as well. It has four domains: physical aspects of disease (5 items), psychological aspects (2 items), social aspects (2 items) and sexuality (2 items).

dataStructure.title: Scales for Outcomes in Parkinson's Disease- Psychosocial (SCOPA-PS)
dataStructure.description: The Scales for Outcomes in PD-Psychological (SCOPA-PS) measures psychosocial functioning in PD.

dataStructure.title: World Health Organization Quality of Life Assessment (WHOQOL-BREF)
dataStructure.description: The WHOQOL-BREF was developed as short version of the WHOQOL-100 for use in situations where time is restricted, where respondent burden must be minimized and where detail is less necessary e.g. large epidemiologic surveys and some clinical trials.

dataStructure.title: International SCI Core Data Set
dataStructure.description: The purpose of the International Spinal Cord Injury (SCI) Core Data Set is to standardize the collection and reporting of a minimal amount of information necessary to evaluate and compare results of published studies. The minimal amount of information includes date of birth and injury, gender, the cause of spinal cord lesion, and the neurologic status.

dataStructure.title: International SCI Lower Urinary Tract Function Basic Data Set
dataStructure.description: Collection of data on lower urinary tract function is universal when individuals with spinal cord lesions consult doctors with knowledge regarding spinal cord lesions. The purpose of the Lower Urinary Tract Function Basic Data Set for Spinal Cord Injury (SCI) individuals is to standardize the collection and reporting of a minimal amount of information on the lower urinary tract in daily practice in accordance with the purpose and vision of the International Spinal Cord Injury Data Sets.

dataStructure.title: International SCI Urodynamic Basic Data Set
dataStructure.description: Collection of data on the urodynamic observations made during urodynamic studies is universal when individuals with spinal cord lesions are evaluated for their lower urinary tract function. The purpose of the Urodynamic Basic Data Set for Spinal Cord Injury (SCI) individuals is to standardize the collection and reporting of a minimal amount of information from the urodynamic study in daily practice in accordance with purpose and vision of the International Spinal Cord Injury Data Sets.

dataStructure.title: International SCI Urinary Tract Imaging Basic Data Set
dataStructure.description: Collection of data on urinary tract imaging is universal when individuals with spinal cord lesions are evaluated for their urinary tract. The purpose of the Urinary Tract Imaging Basic Data Set for Spinal Cord Injury (SCI) is to standardize the collection and reporting of a minimal amount of information on imaging of the urinary tract in daily practice in accordance with the purpose and vision of the International Spinal Cord Injury Data Sets. It is not expected that the present basic data set shall be used in full in any centre for a single individual with SCI. The intention is to give a basic data set for each of the commonly used imaging investigations of the urinary tract.

dataStructure.title: International SCI Bowel Function Basic Data Set
dataStructure.description: The majority of individuals with spinal cord injury (SCI) have neurogenic bowel dysfunction including constipation, fecal incontinence and abdominal pain or discomfort. Constipation related symptoms become significantly more severe with time since injury. In accordance with the aims of the International Spinal Cord Injury Data Sets the aim of the Bowel Function Basic Data Set for Spinal Cord Injury is to standardize the collection and reporting of a minimal amount of information on bowel function in daily practice.

dataStructure.title: International SCI Bowel Function Extended Data Set
dataStructure.description: The majority of individuals with spinal cord injury (SCI) have neurogenic bowel dysfunction including constipation, fecal incontinence and abdominal pain or discomfort. Constipation related symptoms become significantly more severe with time since injury. In accordance with the aims of the International Spinal Cord Injury Data Sets the aim of the Bowel Function Extended Data Set for Spinal Cord Injury is to standardize the collection and reporting of an extended amount of information on bowel function in individuals with SCI.

dataStructure.title: International SCI Pain Basic Data Set Version 2.0
dataStructure.description: Chronic pain is one of the most frequently reported reasons for reduced quality of life following spinal cord injury (SCI). The purpose of the International Spinal Cord Injury Pain Basic Data Set is to standardize the collection and reporting of pain in the SCI population. It contains a minimal amount of clinically relevant information concerning pain that can be collected in the daily practice of healthcare professionals with expertise in SCI. In addition, the evaluation should be logistically feasible in various settings and countries.

dataStructure.title: International SCI Female and Male Sexual Function Basic Data Sets
dataStructure.description: Collection of data on female/male sexual function should routinely be performed when female/male individuals with spinal cord lesions consult doctors with knowledge regarding spinal cord lesions. In addition data on female/male sexual function should routinely be reported in scientific documents related to female/male sexual function and related areas. The purpose of both the Female and Male Sexual Function Basic Data Sets for Spinal Cord Injury (SCI) is to standardize the collection and reporting of a minimal amount of information on female and male sexual function in daily practice in accordance with the purpose and vision of the International Spinal Cord Injury Data Sets. This will also make it possible to evaluate and compare results from various published studies.

dataStructure.title: International Standards for Neurological Classification of SCI Worksheet
dataStructure.description: This worksheet explains the standard method to classify the extent of the spinal cord injury. It includes a dermatome chart, steps in classification, and the American Spinal Cord Injury Association (ASIA) Impairment Scale. The form is freely available but should not be altered without permission from ASIA.

dataStructure.title: International SCI Cardiovascular Function Basic Data Set
dataStructure.description: Cardiovascular abnormalities have been well documented in humans following spinal cord lesions. However, more attention needs to be paid to the documentation of these abnormalities in individuals with spinal cord lesions. The aim of the Cardiovascular Function Basic Data Set for Spinal Cord Injury is to standardize the collection and reporting of a minimal amount of information on cardiovascular function in daily practice. Furthermore, the International Cardiovascular Function Basic SCI Data Set makes it possible to evaluate and compare results from various published studies on cardiovascular dysfunction after SCI. The Cardiovascular Function Basic SCI Data Set is applicable to adults with traumatic or non-traumatic supraconal, conal or cauda equina lesions.

dataStructure.title: International SCI Quality of Life Basic Data Set
dataStructure.description: The purpose of the Quality of Life Basic Data Set is to standardize the collection and reporting of a minimal amount of information necessary to evaluate and compare results of published studies. For the purposes of this data set, and to ensure its international applicability and comparability, we use the definition provided by Wood-Dauphine et al (2002). Wood-Dauphine S, Exner G, and the SCI Consensus Group. Quality of life in patients with spinal cord injury - basic issues, assessment and recommendations. Restorative Neurology and Neuroscience 2002; 20: 135-149.

dataStructure.title: International SCI Pulmonary Basic Data Set
dataStructure.description: The purpose of the International Pulmonary Basic Data Set for Spinal Cord Injury (SCI) individuals is to standardize the collection and reporting of a minimal amount of information on bronchopulmonary function in daily practice in accordance with the purpose and vision of the International Spinal Cord Injury Data Sets. The data in this Pulmonary Basic SCI Data Set generally will be used in connection with data in the International SCI Core Data Set, which includes information on date of birth and injury, gender, the cause of spinal cord lesion, and neurologic status.

dataStructure.title: International SCI Endocrine and Metabolic Function Basic Data Set
dataStructure.description: The purpose of the International SCI Endocrine and Metabolic Function Basic Data Set for individuals with spinal cord lesion is to standardize the collection and reporting of a minimal amount of information on endocrine and metabolic function in daily practice in accordance with the purpose and vision of the International SCI Data Sets. This will also make it possible to evaluate and compare results from various published studies. In addition, the International SCI Core Data Set contains information on whether a vertebral injury was present, whether spinal surgery was performed, whether associated injuries were present, whether the patient with a spinal cord lesion was ventilator-dependent at the time of discharge from initial inpatient care, and the place of discharge from initial inpatient care.

dataStructure.title: International SCI Spinal Column Injury Basic Data Set
dataStructure.description: The aim of the International SCI Spinal Column Injury Basic Data Set is to standardize the collection and reporting of a minimal amount of clinically relevant information on spinal column injury useful both for recording in daily practice and for reporting and basic analysis of spinal cord and spinal column trauma. The International SCI Spinal Column Injury Basic Data Set makes it possible to evaluate data related to spinal column injuries and achieve comparability between scientific publications on SCI. It is applicable to skeletally mature and skeletally immature individuals with traumatic spinal cord injuries. The International SCI Spinal Column Injury Basic Data Set should be used primarily in connection with the background information collected in the International SCI Core Data Set.

dataStructure.title: International SCI Skin and Thermoregulation Function Basic Data Set
dataStructure.description: The aim of the Skin and Thermoregulation Function Basic Data Set for Spinal Cord Injury is to standardize the collection and reporting of a minimal amount of information on these issues in daily practice. It is applicable to adult individuals with traumatic or non-traumatic supraconal, conal or cauda equina lesions. The International SCI Skin and Thermoregulation Function Basic Data Set will mostly be used in connection with the background information within the International SCI Core Data Set. This specifically applies to the documentation of the level, completeness and time post spinal cord lesions, which play an important role on skin and thermoregulation parameters following injury. The International SCI Skin and Thermoregulation Function Basic Data Set may be used once yearly in chronic SCI individuals.

dataStructure.title: International SCI Musculoskeletal Basic Data Set
dataStructure.description: The purpose of the International SCI Musculoskeletal Basic Data Set is to standardize the collection and reporting of a minimal amount of information about musculoskeletal status in accordance with the purpose and vision of the International Spinal Cord Injury Data Sets. Standardisation of data collection and reporting is central to valid comparisons across sites and published papers. It is intended that the International SCI Musculoskeletal Basic Data Set be used in connection with the International SCI Core Data Set.

dataStructure.title: International Non-Traumatic Spinal Cord Injury Basic and Extended Data Sets
dataStructure.description: It is well known that damage to the neural elements in the spinal canal (spinal cord and cauda equina) resulting in resolving or permanent neurological deficit can arise from many causes other than trauma. Although there is no universally accepted term for spinal cord damage not due to trauma (often referred to as non-traumatic spinal cord injury [NTSCI] - but better alternatives may be spinal cord damage' or spinal cord myelopathy') this field is an important aspect of spinal cord medicine. International consensus on a classification system for NTSCI is essential in order to have good epidemiological studies, prevention, treatment, and outcomes research and to facilitate comparative studies across different settings. The International Data Sets for NTSCI includes a classification system for the aetiology of NTSCI.

dataStructure.title: Demographics
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that are collected to describe the demographics of the study population relevant to Friedreich's Ataxia research. [Examples of CDEs included: General CDE demographic elements (gender, race, ethnicity, etc.); additional race information]

dataStructure.title: Social Status
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that are collected to describe the social status of the study population relevant to FA research. [Examples of CDEs included: General CDE demographic elements and additional information (education)]

dataStructure.title: Medical History
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements related to the study participant's/ subject's health history. (Examples of CDEs included: review of symptoms and conditions in specific body systems (pulmonary, endocrine, musculoskeletal, etc.)

dataStructure.title: Family History
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that determine if FA or other related diseases/disorders run in the participant's/ subject's immediate family. (Examples of CDEs included: History of Friedreich's Ataxia, History of Ataxia )

dataStructure.title: Prenatal and Perinatal History
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that pertain to pregnancy and perinatal history [Examples of CDEs included: Mother's age at the time she gave birth to the participant/subject; Number of live born children the participant/subject's mother has delivered]

dataStructure.title: Pregnancy History
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that pertain to pregnancy and perinatal history [Examples of CDEs included: Does participant/subject have a history of prior pregnancy?]

dataStructure.title: Pediatric Developmental History
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that pertain to participant/ subject's developmental history [Examples of CDEs included: History of Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD) or Attention Deficit Disorder (ADD), delayed acquisition of language/cognitive milestones, diagnosed by a pediatrician or neurologist?]

dataStructure.title: Behavioral History
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that pertain to participant's/ subject's behavior and social history. (Examples of CDEs included: Alcohol and Illicit Drug Use History and Smoking History)

dataStructure.title: History Data Source and Reliability
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that pertain to the data source and reliability of the information gathered in a study. (Examples of CDEs included: how the medical/family history information was obtained, Overall assessment of the reliability of the medical/family history information obtained)

dataStructure.title: Medical History of Friedreich's Ataxia
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements related to the participant's/ subject's health history related specifically to Friedreich's Ataxia. (Examples of CDEs included: hearing, vision, etc. affected by FA)

dataStructure.title: Physical Examination
dataStructure.description: The physical exam is generally administered at screening and/or baseline to determine study eligibility. It may also be administered at follow-up visits to track a participant's/subject's physical status. This CRF Module captures the physical exam results.

dataStructure.title: Vital Signs
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements captured at study visits to help monitor the health of the participant/ subject and in clinical trials to help assess the safety of the intervention. (Examples of CDEs included: Heart rate; Blood pressure; and Temperature)

dataStructure.title: Laboratory Tests
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements related to laboratory tests commonly used in FA clinical research studies. (Examples of CDEs included: Lab test name; Lab test result; and Lab test unit)

dataStructure.title: Cardiac Magnetic Resonance Imaging
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements collected when a Cardiac and Magnetics Resonance Imaging is performed to evaluate a participant's/subject's cardiac health. (Examples of CDEs included: Relative wall thickness, Left ventricle mass, Ejection fraction)

dataStructure.title: Electrocardiogram
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements collected when an electrocardiogram is performed to evaluate a participant's/subject's cardiac health. (Examples of CDEs included: PR interval; QRS duration; and Heart rhythm)

dataStructure.title: Echocardiogram
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that measure the participant's/subject's heart function. (Examples of CDEs included: Left ventricular end-systolic internal dimension; Fractional shortening)

dataStructure.title: Holter Exam
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that monitor the participant's/subject's heart rhythms for 24 hours. (Examples of CDEs included: Maximum heart rate; Episodes of heart block; Premature atrial contractions)

dataStructure.title: Prior and Concomitant Medications
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements relating to participant's/ subject's medication history (Examples of CDEs included: neurological agents/vitamins, diabetic medication(s), heart medications)

dataStructure.title: Activities of Daily Living and Gait
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that determine participant's/ subject's ability to complete activities of daily living. (Examples of CDEs included: current level of swallowing, speech, dressing, etc.)

dataStructure.title: Bladder Control Scale (BLCS)
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements for the Bladder Control Scale. [Examples of CDEs included: lost control of your bladder or had an accident; almost lost control of your bladder or had an accident]

dataStructure.title: Bowel Control Scale (BWCS)
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements for the Bowel Control Scale. [Examples of CDEs included: been constipated; lost control of your bowels or had an accident]

dataStructure.title: Friedreich's Ataxia Impact Scale (FAIS)
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements for the Friedreich's Ataxia Impact Scale (FAIS). [Examples of CDEs included: As a result of your Friedreich's Ataxia, how much in the past two weeks have you been bothered by loss of balance? Being clumsy? Weakness in muscles?]

dataStructure.title: Friedreich's Ataxia Rating Scale (FARS)
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements for the Friedreich's Ataxia Rating Scale. [Examples of CDEs included: functional staging for ataxia; speech]

dataStructure.title: Tardieu Scale
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that comprise the Tardieu Scale.

dataStructure.title: Cardiac End Points
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements pertaining to cardiac end points. (Examples of CDEs included: FA End Points Hospitalizations in past year, FA End Points Start Date of hospitalization)

dataStructure.title: Demographics
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that are collected to describe the demographics of the study population relevant to ALS research. [Examples of CDEs included: General CDE demographic elements (gender, race, ethnicity, etc.); additional race information]

dataStructure.title: Social Status
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that are collected to describe the social status of the study population relevant to ALS research. [Examples of CDEs included: General CDE demographic elements and additional information (education)]

dataStructure.title: Medical History
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that are collected to describe the medical history of the study population relevant to ALS research [Examples of CDEs included: allergies and childbearing questions]

dataStructure.title: Family History
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that determine if ALS or other related diseases/disorders run in the participant's/ subject's immediate family. (Examples of CDEs included: Diagnosis of ALS, FTD or Other Neurological Disorder]

dataStructure.title: Symptom, Sign, Diagnosis Criteria
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that pertain to diagnosis criteria for ALS [Examples of CDEs include symptom onset date and diagnosis date]

dataStructure.title: Genetics
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that are collected to detail which mutations have been tested and the outcome [Examples of CDEs included: Genes screened, mutations found ]

dataStructure.title: Physical Examination
dataStructure.description: The physical exam is generally administered at screening and/or baseline to determine study eligibility. It may also be administered at follow-up visits to track a participant's/subject's physical status. This CRF Module captures the physical exam results.

dataStructure.title: Neuromuscular Examination
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements that are collected during a neuromuscular examination [Examples of CDEs include: cranial segment, cervical segment, thoracic segment]

dataStructure.title: Vital Signs
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements related to vital signs commonly used in ALS clinical research studies. (Examples of CDEs included: Temperature, Blood Pressure, Weight)

dataStructure.title: Laboratory Tests
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements related to laboratory tests commonly used in ALS clinical research studies. (Examples of CDEs included: Lab test name; Lab test result; and Lab test unit)

dataStructure.title: Tissue Based Marker Collection
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements related to Tissue Markers commonly used in ALS clinical research studies. [Examples of CDEs included: Was muscle biopsy done, Was skin biopsy done]

dataStructure.title: Fasting Information
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements related to Tissue Markers commonly used in ALS clinical research studies. [Examples of CDEs included: Data and Time participant last ate; Date and Time participant last drank caffeine]

dataStructure.title: Resting Energy Expenditure
dataStructure.description: Includes information on resting energy expenditure

dataStructure.title: Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI)
dataStructure.description: Contains data elements related to collection of information using MRI commonly used in ALS clinical research studies. [Examples of CDEs included: T1-MRI sequence parameters, Magnetic Field Strength of Scanner Used]
